re, Auvergne, Frankrig","Wittingham, Surrey, England":"Surrey, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"about 1121–about 1203":"circa 1121–circa 1203","1119–1178":"1119–1178","1137–1199":"1137–1199","1121–1203":"1121–1203","1137":"1137","1203":"1203","1178":"1178","1199":"1199","1121":"1121","about 1203":"circa 1203","about 1121":"circa 1121","1119":"1119","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","England":"England","Willingham, Surry, England":"Willingham, Lincolnshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Borne, Haute-Loire, Auvergne, France":"Borne, Haute-Loire, Auvergne, Frankrijk","Wittingham, Surrey, England":"Surrey, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1121–about 1203":"about 1121–about 1203","1119–1178":"1119–1178","1137–1199":"1137–1199","1121–1203":"1121–1203","1137":"1137","1203":"1203","1178":"1178","1199":"1199","1121":"1121","about 1203":"about 1203","about 1121":"about 1121","1119":"1119","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","England":"England","Willingham, Surry, England":"Willingham, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Borne, Haute-Loire, Auvergne, France":"Borne, Haute-Loire, Auvergne, France","Wittingham, Surrey, England":"Surrey, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Born","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Kurt, Otto, Heinz, Helmut, Berthold, Frieda, Friedrich, Fritz, Gerhard, Horst, Jutta.","English: variant of   Bourne  .","English (of Norman origin): nickname from Old French <i>borgne</i> ‘one-eyed, squint-eyed’."],"variants":[{"name":"Bourne","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived beside a stream, from southern Middle English <i>bourne</i>, Old English <i>burna</i>, <i>burne</i> ‘spring, stream’, or a habitational name from a place called with this word, for example Bourn in Cambridgeshire or Bourne in Lincolnshire. In surnames the reference is often to an old stream called <i>burna</i>, surviving as the name of a farm. This word was replaced as the general word for a stream in southern dialects by Old English <i>brōc</i> (see   Brook  ) and came to be restricted in meaning to a stream flowing only intermittently, especially in winter."]},{"name":"Borner","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Gerd, Hans, Irmgard.","North German (also <b>Börner</b>): variant of   Born  , + the suffix <i>-er</i> denoting an inhabitant.","North German: occupational name for a stockman, from Middle Low German <i>bornen</i> ‘to water (farm animals)’."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Richard de Born was born about 1121, in London, Middlesex, England. He had at least 1 daughter with Matilda Aleanore De Dommart. He died about 1203, in Willingham, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 84."},"et":{"about 1121–about 1203":"umbes 1121–umbes 1203","1119–1178":"1119–1178","1137–1199":"1137–1199","1121–1203":"1121–1203","1137":"1137","1203":"1203","1178":"1178","1199":"1199","1121":"1121","about 1203":"umbes 1203","about 1121":"umbes 1121","1119":"1119","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","England":"England","Willingham, Surry, England":"Willingham, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Borne, Haute-Loire, Auvergne, France":"Borne, Haute-Loire, Auvergne, Prantsusmaa","Wittingham, Surrey, England":"Surrey, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1121–about 1203":"noin 1121–noin 1203","1119–1178":"1119–1178","1137–1199":"1137–1199","1121–1203":"1121–1203","1137":"1137","1203":"1203","1178":"1178","1199":"1199","1121":"1121","about 1203":"noin 1203","about 1121":"noin 1121","1119":"1119","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","England":"England","Willingham, S